| Notes                   = * The film was announced during Marvel Studios' event at El Capitan Theatre on October 28, 2014.{{cite|ref=true|refname=Annoucement|url=http://www.newsarama.com/22570-marvel-studios-event-live.html|title=Marvel Studios Event|work=Newsarama|first=Tom|last=McLean|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014}}
* This film's original release date was November 3, 2017, but when Marvel announced plans for ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'', they pushed it back to July 6, 2018 and ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' took its original release date. The film was later moved forward to its current release date, with ''[[Ant-Man and the Wasp (film)|Ant-Man and the Wasp]]'' taking its previous one.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/23548/chadwick_boseman_to_star_in_marvels_black_panther|title=Chadwick Boseman to Star in Marvel's Black Panther|work=Marvel|first=Marc|last=Strom|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=10 February 2015}}{{cite|ref=true|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/24065/marvel_studios_schedules_new_release_dates_for_4_films|title=Marvel Studios Schedules New Release Dates for 4 Films|work=Marvel|first=Marc|last=Strom|date=9 February 2015|accessdate=10 May 2015}}{{cite|ref=true|url=http://marvel.com/news/movies/25244/marvel_studios_phase_3_update?linkId=17794776|title=MARVEL STUDIOS PHASE 3 UPDATE|work=Marvel|first=Marc|last=Strom|date=9 October 2015|accessdate=9 October 2015}}
* Filming for this film started by January 21, 2017, and wrapped on April 19, 2017.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/martin-freeman-chadwick-boseman-spotted-black-panther-set/|title= Martin Freeman, Chadwick Boseman And More Spotted On Black Panther Set|work= We Got This Covered|last= Wilding|first= Josh|date= 2017-01-21|accessdate= 2017-12-12}}{{cite|ref=true|url= https://screenrant.com/marvel-black-panther-done-filming/|title= Marvel’s Black Panther Wraps Filming|work= Screen Rant|last= Erao|first= Matthew|date= 2017-04-20|accessdate= 2017-12-12}}
* On February 9, 2018, {{WP|Interscope Records}} released a soundtrack for this film titled ''{{WP|Black Panther (soundtrack)|Black Panther: The Album}}'', which was curated by {{WP|Kendrick Lamar}} and his record label {{WP|Top Dawg Entertainment}}.
* With a domestic total box office gross of $700 million, this film became the highest-grossing domestic film of 2018,{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2018&p=.htm|title= 2018 DOMESTIC GROSSES|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= January 10, 2019}} the highest-grossing comic book film of all-time in the US and the highest-grossing stand-alone superhero film worldwide.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/03/26/black-panther-more-box-office-milestones-as-soars-past-the-avengers/Vol 1 70623e0661d3|title='Black Panther' Broke More Box Office Records As It Topped 'Avengers'|work=Forbes|last=Mendelson|first=Scott|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=9 April 2018}}
* With a worldwide total box office gross of about $1,347 billion, this film became the second-highest-grossing film of 2018,{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2018&p=.htm|title= 2018 Yearly Box Office Results|accessdate= January 10, 2019|work= Box Office Mojo}} and at its peak the 9th-highest-grossing film of all time.{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Worldwide Box Office|accessdate= January 10, 2019|work= Box Office Mojo|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190110152830/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|archivedate= January 10, 2019}}
* On November 29th, 2020, the Walt Disney Co. retroactively changed the opening credits of the film on Disney+ to instead solely feature scenes, concept art, and behind-the-scenes footage of Chadwick Boseman as Black Panther, in order to pay tribute to the late actor on what would've been his 44th birthday. 
| Trivia                  = * The release date for this film was during [[wikipedia:Black History Month|Black History Month]].
* Black Panther's main costume for this film was designed by [[Adi Granov]], who had previously designed the main armor for the 2008 film ''[[Iron Man (film)|Iron Man]]''.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.facebook.com/AdiGranovIllustration/posts/10155686800823598|title=Adi Granov Illustration|work=Facebook|first=Tamsin|last=Granov|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=16 October 2017}}
* Early into the film's development, director Ryan Coogler and co-writer Joe Robert Cole considered having [[Elijah Bradley]] be part of its cast of characters. The idea ended up going away in favor of focusing on Wakanda even more.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2305062/the-cool-marvel-comics-character-ryan-coogler-considered-for-black-panther|title=The Cool Marvel Comics Character Ryan Coogler Considered For Black Panther|work=Cinema Blend|first=Eric|last=Eisenberg|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=1 February 2018}}
* Director Ryan Coogler is a fan of the [[Spider-Man]] villain [[Kraven the Hunter]], and early into the film's development requested to have him in it, but was denied.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/ryan-coogler-wanted-spider-man-villain-black-panther-exclusive-133330486.html|title=Ryan Coogler reveals which Spider-Man villain he wanted for Black Panther (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Yahoo Movies UK|first=Sam|last=Ashurst|date=9 February 2018|accessdate=9 February 2018}}
* Initially, Coogler went back and forth on the order of the scenes set in Oakland and the UN. He settled on ending the movie with the scene in Oakland both to serve as a book-end and because of its bigger emotional impact.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cbr.com/black-panther-alternate-ending-revealed|title=Ryan Coogler Reveals Black Panther’s Alternate Ending|work=CBR.com|first=Tom|last=Chapman|date=21 February 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018}}
* The wardrobe worn by T'Challa, Okoye and Nakia during their undercover mission in Busan references the colors of the {{WP|Pan-African flag}}. T'Challa is dressed in black, Okoye in red, and Nakia in green. In that very same scene, Ulysses Klaue's vest is blue, representing colonialism.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SNHc2PxY8lY|title=Black Panther's Director Ryan Coogler Breaks Down a Fight Scene | Notes on a Scene|work=Vanity Fair|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018}}
* Mirroring the final scene of the movie, The Walt Disney Company announced that they would donate $1 million to the {{WP|Boys & Girls Club of America}} to help expand their youth STEM programs, which would include a STEM Center of Innovation to be established in Oakland, California.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/extras/news/925705-disney-to-help-open-stem-center-in-oakland-after-black-panthers-success|title=Disney to Help Open STEM Center in Oakland After Black Panther’s Success|work=ComingSoon.net|first=Spencer|last=Perry|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=26 February 2018}}
* In the film, the people of [[Wakanda]] speak {{WP|Xhosa language|Xhosa}}, one of the real world official languages of [[South Africa]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/41684-black-panther-african-language-wakanda-xhosa|title=Why Wakandans Speak Xhosa, an Actual African Language|work=Inverse|first=Eric|last=Francisco|date=1 March 2018|accessdate=2 March 2018}}
* The scene of the robbery at the Museum of Great Britain was inspired by director Coogler's own visit to the British Museum while in the UK during the press tour for his film {{WP|Creed (film)|Creed}}.{{cite|ref=true|refname=11 Secrets|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/11-black-panther-secrets-ryan-coogler-nate-moore/|title=11 Black Panther secrets from Ryan Coogler and Nate Moore|work=Empire|first=Ben|last=Travis|date=1 March 2018|accessdate=12 March 2018}}
* For the mid-credits scene, Coogler and his wife looked into different African proverbs to go with T'Challa's speech. The line of "In times of crisis, the wise build bridges while the foolish build barriers" is apparently so ancient that many African tribes claim it.<ref name="11 Secrets"/>
* Oakland was chosen as Killmonger's home city to some extent because it was the home of {{WP|Tupac Shakur}}. Coogler specifically noted that "We wanted to bring the energy of Tupac to a Marvel movie. That's where 'Pac spent a lot of his time, the 'Pac that we know came from his time in the Bay Area. Black people got to California and the Bay Area from repeated migration, fleeing awful things. And that's where you saw these organizations [like the Black Panther Party] come from. They ran out of places to run."<ref name="11 Secrets"/>
* The death of Ulysses Klaue was written in part a parallel to the search for {{WP|Osama Bin Laden}}, with director Coogler noting that "What if somebody else brought Bin Laden in instead of Obama? For T'Challa, it's all-important that he gets this guy, it's very important to him, his country. And then somebody else does it and throws it in his face."
* The 2015 black-and-white film ''{{WP|Embrace of the Serpent}}'' helped shape Killmonger's point of view, specifically in regards to Killmonger's connection to Wakanda. As explained by Coogler: "Killmonger had a connection to Wakanda, but the connection was taken away from him before he could mature. All he really has of Wakanda is his book, his broken ideas of what it is. He adopts things from African cultures, but in a way it's corrupted. Scarification on the continent of Africa is not what you do for killing people, but he's adopted it to that. He has the worst tendencies of both places."<ref name="11 Secrets"/>
* Black Panther was introduced in ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' so that his movie could skip "all of the origin story pitfalls and just tell a cool story."<ref name="11 Secrets"/>
* Before it was settled that N'Jobu was going to narrate the prologue, it was considered to have T'Chaka or even Shuri delivering the history of Wakanda.<ref name="11 Secrets"/>
* There were two versions of the post-credits scene considered, one in which Bucky sported a new metallic arm. Director Coogler opted to go with the final choice so that Bucky could feel "more human."<ref name="11 Secrets"/>
* This is currently the highest-rated movie in the MCU on Rotten Tomatoes at 97%. The closest one is [[Avengers: Endgame]], at 94%.

